{
  "text": "In any case, the tails of longevity in Table 2 are astounding. For Japanese women today, the maximum span of life is a mere 16 percent higher than the top tenth percentile. For yeast, medflies, and parasitoid wasps, however, maximum life span is more than triple the advanced old age that only a tenth of the population attains. So long for some invertebrates and so short for modern humans: this is a tail on which to hang a tale-of reliability. Acsadi and Nemeskéri (1970) ; these data may not be reliable. In particular, it is unlikely that the maximum age actually was 100 (Jeune and Vaupel 1995, 1999) . More likely it was 85 or 90, which would give a value of t of 0.37 or 0.45. Numerous life tables based on age estimation of skeletal remains have been published, but the methods are highly questionable [CITATION_1] ",
